# AI Provider Constraints

This project supports **three** providers: **Gemini** (Google), **Groq** (Llama)
and **Ollama** (self-hosted, typically on Railway). Valid provider keys live in
`app.ai_store.VALID_PROVIDERS` (`{"gemini", "groq", "ollama"}`). Each event
type stores an **ordered fallback chain** in `ai_provider_config.provider`
(JSON list up to `app.ai_store.MAX_PROVIDER_CHAIN` entries, no duplicates),
editable from the admin panel as 4 priority selects. Legacy enum strings
like `"gemini_fallback_groq"` are still parsed at read time for backward
compatibility.

## Groq limits

- `GROQ_MAX_PROMPT_CHARS = 10000` — total prompt must fit in ~10k characters
- When building context for Groq, ALWAYS use `_build_context(groups, max_chars=...)` to avoid mid-line truncation
- Never send a raw large prompt to Groq; calculate the overhead of the prompt template and fit the context within the remaining budget
- Groq uses `response_format={"type": "json_object"}` — prompts must ask for JSON

## Gemini limits

- Gemini handles large contexts well (100k+ tokens)
- It's safe to send 150+ groups to Gemini without truncation
- Gemini does NOT enforce JSON output format — rely on prompt instructions

## Ollama limits

- `OLLAMA_MAX_PROMPT_CHARS = 12000` — treat like Groq: build compact context
- `OLLAMA_TIMEOUT = 120` — **default only**. The effective per-call timeout is
  read at invocation time from `ai_runtime_config` via
  `app.ai_store.get_ollama_timeout()` and tunable from the admin panel
  ("Timeout de invocación Ollama", bounds `OLLAMA_TIMEOUT_MIN`=30 /
  `OLLAMA_TIMEOUT_MAX`=900). First call after idle can take 15–40s (cold
  start); keep `OLLAMA_KEEP_ALIVE=10m` on the Railway service. The timeout
  is applied per-request via `httpx.Timeout`, so the cached `AsyncClient`
  is NOT rebuilt when the admin changes it.
- Uses Ollama's native `/api/chat` with `format: "json"` to constrain output
- Default model is `qwen3:8b` (override via `OLLAMA_MODEL` env var)
- Self-hosted → cost per token is 0 by default (seeded from `MODEL_PRICING`).
  The pricing live in the `ai_model_pricing` table and are editable from
  the admin panel; `compute_cost` reads them with a 30 s cache.
- Requires `OLLAMA_BASE_URL` env var (e.g. `http://ollama.railway.internal:11434`)

## Provider routing

- `get_provider_config()` returns `{event_type: [providers...]}`; the list is
  the user-ordered fallback chain.
- `_provider_chain(providers)` filters the stored list down to known
  providers (keeps order, drops unknowns, falls back to `["gemini", "groq"]`
  if the chain is empty/invalid).
- `_run_provider_chain(...)` walks the chain, logging every attempt to
  `ai_usage_log` so the admin monitor always reflects the real state.
- Filter by `_available_providers()` before trying — missing credentials
  skip the provider and fall through to the next.

## Quota guard (proactive RPM/TPM/RPD/TPD + USD/mes)

To avoid hammering providers with known-bad requests (429s from portals) and
to keep paid tiers within budget, `_run_provider_chain` runs a **local
precheck** before every invocation:

- `app.ai_store.PROVIDER_LIMIT_DEFAULTS` holds hardcoded monthly-researched
  defaults per `(provider, model)` for RPM/TPM/RPD/TPD plus a `monthly_usd`
  USD budget (default `None` → unlimited). Ollama defaults are all `None`
  (self-hosted → no external cap), but the admin can set explicit values to
  cap CPU spend on the self-hosted infra; those overrides ARE enforced (see
  hard-cap rules below).
- Admin overrides live in the `ai_provider_limits` table (5 nullable columns:
  `rpm`, `tpm`, `rpd`, `tpd`, `monthly_usd`) and are edited from the "Límites
  de proveedores IA" card (Administración tab). Setting a field to empty
  reverts that field to the default; "Restaurar default" deletes the whole
  row.
- A separate **global** USD budget lives in `ai_runtime_config` under
  `monthly_budget_usd_global` (helpers `get_global_monthly_budget` /
  `set_global_monthly_budget`, edited from the same UI block above the
  per-card grid). It's the techo total de la cuenta, sumado sobre todos los
  proveedores.
- `get_provider_limit(provider, model)` merges defaults + overrides and is
  cached for 30 s (`_limits_cache`).
- `query_provider_usage(provider)` counts successful rows in `ai_usage_log`
  inside two rolling windows — 60 s for RPM/TPM and 24 h for RPD/TPD — using
  the `idx_aul_provider_created` index. Cached 10 s per provider
  (`_usage_cache`).
- `query_provider_cost_summary(provider)` and `query_global_cost_summary()`
  suman `cost_total` (filtrado por `success=1`) en dos ventanas: el mes
  calendario en curso (ART) y el día en curso. Cacheados 10 s en
  `_cost_cache`.
- `compute_daily_cap(monthly_budget, month_used)` deriva un cap diario
  auto-ajustado:
  `daily_cap = max(0, (monthly_budget - month_used) / days_remaining)`. Si
  gastás menos un día, el siguiente sube; si te pasás, baja. No se persiste,
  se calcula en cada precheck.
- `_quota_blocked(provider)` evalúa, en este orden, y devuelve el primer
  nombre que dispare:
  1. `monthly_usd_global` — `month_cost_global >= global_budget`
  2. `daily_usd_global` — `today_cost_global >= compute_daily_cap(global)`
  3. `infra_usd_daily` / `infra_usd_monthly` — tope de Railway (solo Ollama).
  4. `monthly_usd` — `month_cost_provider >= pair_budget`
  5. `daily_usd` — `today_cost_provider >= compute_daily_cap(pair)`
  6. `rpm` / `tpm` / `rpd` / `tpd` — cupos del portal o caps manuales.

  Para Ollama, los pasos 6 sólo disparan si el admin configuró el campo a
  mano (default es `None`); el resto aplica igual que a cualquier proveedor.
  Devuelve `None` cuando todo está OK y swallow-ea DB errors fail-open.
- En `_run_provider_chain`, si `_quota_blocked` devuelve non-`None` el step
  se saltea sin gastar API y se loggea como
  `error_type="QuotaExhausted:<field>"`, `error_phase="precheck"`, cero
  tokens. El corte aplica **siempre**, incluso para el último proveedor de
  la cadena: si todos están sobre cupo, `_run_provider_chain` levanta
  `QuotaExhaustedError` y los callers usan su fallback (cache,
  `_last_good_topics`, etc.). No hay "última bala": insistir contra un
  provider con TPD/RPD agotado sólo dispara 429s y suma latencia, y los
  caps en USD o de infra son topes intencionales del admin que tampoco
  conviene bypassear.
- `GET /api/admin/ai-limits` devuelve `{items, defaults, global}`. Cada item
  incluye `monthly_usd`, `monthly_usd_used`, `daily_usd_cap`, `daily_usd_used`
  además de los conteos RPM/TPM/RPD/TPD; `blocked_by` puede ahora contener
  `"monthly_usd"` o `"daily_usd"`. El bloque `global` tiene la misma forma con
  los nombres `monthly_usd_global` / `daily_usd_global` en `blocked_by`.
- `POST /api/admin/ai-limits` acepta `monthly_usd` como float ≥0 o `null`.
- `GET/POST /api/admin/ai-budget-global` administran el presupuesto global
  (`{"monthly_usd": 50.0}`, `{"monthly_usd": null}` o `{"reset": true}`).
- Cualquier write invalida `_limits_cache`, `_usage_cache` y `_cost_cache`.
  Para reset manual, usar `invalidate_provider_limits()` y
  `invalidate_provider_usage_cache()` — ambos se llaman automáticamente desde
  los endpoints admin.

> **Nota sobre Ollama y Groq free tier**: el seed de `ai_model_pricing` los
> marca como $0/token, así que los presupuestos USD nunca los bloquean por
> default. Si un proveedor deja de ser free, el admin puede actualizar el
> precio desde la card "Precio por 1M tokens" → "Actualizar valores" sin
> deploy y los caps quedan activos al instante.

## Editable pricing (`ai_model_pricing` table)

- Cada row tiene `(provider, model, input_usd_per_1m, output_usd_per_1m,
  source_url, updated_at)`. PK por `(provider, model)`.
- Seed inicial desde `MODEL_PRICING` y `PRICING_SOURCE_URLS` durante
  `init_ai_tables()`. El seed solo inserta rows que no existen, así no
  pisa overrides al deployar.
- `compute_cost(model, in_tokens, out_tokens)` lee la tabla via
  `_load_pricing_from_db` con cache de 30 s (`_pricing_cache`); si el row
  no existe cae al `MODEL_PRICING` hardcodeado y, en última instancia, a
  `(0.0, 0.0)`. **Nunca crashea** una llamada de logging.
- Helpers públicos: `get_model_pricing()`, `get_model_pricing_for(p, m)`,
  `set_model_pricing(p, m, in_$/1M, out_$/1M)`,
  `reset_model_pricing(p, m)` (restaura defaults), `is_default_model_pricing`.
- Endpoints admin: `GET /api/admin/ai-pricing` devuelve `{items, source_urls}`,
  `POST /api/admin/ai-pricing` upsertea o resetea (`{reset: true}`).
- UI: en la card de cada proveedor (Administración → Límites de proveedores
  IA), el bloque "Precio por 1M tokens" muestra in/out actuales + último
  update; el link "Actualizar valores ↗" abre la página oficial de pricing
  Y desplega un form inline para guardar valores nuevos sin reload.

## Railway infra spend caps

- Solo aplica a Ollama (lo único que corre sobre Railway). Los proveedores
  cloud no se ven afectados por estos caps.
- Almacenamiento: `ai_runtime_config` con las claves `infra_usd_daily_max`
  y `infra_usd_monthly_max` (None = sin límite). Helpers en
  `app.infra_cost_store`: `get_infra_limits()`, `set_infra_limits()`.
- `get_current_spend()` devuelve `{today_usd, month_usd, fetched_at}`:
  - `month_usd` = `estimated_usd_month` del último snapshot agregado
    (Railway ya reporta acumulado del período de billing).
  - `today_usd` = `month_usd_now − baseline`. La baseline se elige así, de
    mejor a peor:
      1. último snapshot **anterior al día actual** (típico del cron de
         ayer): permite calcular gasto diario con 1 solo snapshot nuevo
         de hoy, ideal cuando hay historia continua;
      2. primer snapshot del día actual, si no hay nada anterior y ya
         existen ≥2 snapshots dentro del día;
      3. `None` (guard permisivo) si solo hay 1 snapshot total y nada
         antes.
- `get_blocked_keys()` devuelve un subset de `["daily", "monthly"]`. Cache
  de 30 s (`_spend_cache`) que se resetea cuando se guarda un snapshot
  nuevo o se cambian los límites.
- Endpoints admin: `GET /api/admin/infra-limits` → `{limits, spend, blocked,
  available}` (donde `available=False` si Railway no está configurado);
  `POST /api/admin/infra-limits` con `{daily_max, monthly_max}` o
  `{reset: true}`.
- Guardrail: `_infra_block_reason(provider)` en `ai_search.py` se llama
  desde `_quota_blocked` antes de los caps por par. Si Railway no está
  configurado o no hay datos, devuelve `None` (permisivo). Caso contrario
  emite `"infra_usd_monthly"` o `"infra_usd_daily"`. Ambos son **hard
  caps** (no se bypasean ni en último step de la cadena).

### Monthly research TODO

The numeric defaults in `PROVIDER_LIMIT_DEFAULTS` are marked with a
`# Lookup YYYY-MM-DD` comment. Once a month, re-check Google AI Studio and
Groq Console, update the numbers, and bump the date. Para pricing,
hacer lo propio con `MODEL_PRICING` (defaults hardcodeados que se usan en
el seed de `ai_model_pricing` y como fallback). El admin puede patchear
los valores desde la UI sin deploy en cualquiera de los dos casos.

## When changing search or topic prompts

1. Check that `max_groups` and `max_chars` are appropriate for ALL THREE providers
2. If increasing context size, verify Groq and Ollama still receive well-formed prompts (not truncated mid-line)
3. Use `_call_ai_search()` for search (builds separate prompts per provider) instead of generic `_call_ai()`
4. Test with `py -m pytest tests/unit/test_ai_search.py -q` after changes

## Context budget calculation pattern

```python
prompt_overhead = len(TEMPLATE.format(query=query, context=""))
budget = MAX_PROMPT_CHARS - prompt_overhead - 100  # safety margin
context = _build_context(groups, max_groups=150, max_chars=max(budget, 2000))
```

## Debugging Ollama timeouts

When an invocation fails with `error_phase=read` ("Ollama read timeout"),
`httpx` already guarantees the request was fully delivered before the
timeout fired. To confirm end-to-end and inspect what the model is doing,
cross-check against Ollama's own surfaces:

- `journalctl -u ollama -f --since "5 min ago"` (systemd) or
  `docker logs -f ollama --since 5m` (docker/Railway) — confirms the
  incoming HTTP request and shows prompt tokenization / model load lines.
- `curl http://<host>:11434/api/ps` — lists models currently resident in
  VRAM/RAM with their idle time. If the target model isn't listed (or was
  evicted), the timeout is explained by a cold load.
- `curl http://<host>:11434/api/tags` — sanity check that Ollama itself is
  up and reachable from where you're testing.
- Correlate the `request_sent_at` field shown in the admin modal with the
  timestamp of the incoming request line in Ollama's logs to prove arrival.

The `prompt_preview` column in `ai_usage_log` is persisted automatically
on any failed call whose provider string contains `ollama` (including
fallback combinations), even when `AI_LOG_PREVIEWS=0`. That lets you open
the failed invocation in the admin panel and inspect the actual prompt
that reached the model without flipping the global flag.
